    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-09-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-09-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.77–143</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chief of Division of Latin-American
                            Affairs</gloss> to Mr. <persName type="to">R. L. Farnham</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-09-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 28, 1916</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Farnham</hi>: Pursuant to our conversation of
                    yesterday, I take pleasure in transmitting herewith a copy of the French text of
                    the reply of the Minister of Haiti to the memorandum of the National Railway
                    Company of Haiti, regarding the differences now obtaining between the Government
                    and the railroad, together with a copy of the translation thereof.<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d434fn7">Printed ante, inclosure to note from the Minister of Haiti,
                        dated September 21, 1916, <ref target="#pg_379">p. 379</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>As I have already informed you, we shall, upon receipt of advice from you, be
                    happy to arrange with Minister Ménos a date mutually satisfactory for the first
                    oral discussion of the points at issue, during which the Department will, of
                    course, be happy to lend its good offices.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. Butler Wright</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
